re is particularly concerned with how, as a result of their encounters in the classroom, chapel, kitchen, and farmyard, Māori and the English mutually influenced each other's worldviews. Concluding in 1840 with New Zealand's formal colonization, this book offers an important contribution to debates over religion and empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMaori (New Zealand people)xMissionsxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Australia & New Zealand.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375883zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822375883/original  a978-3-11-071182-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles